This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Few individuals have had the impact on
science fiction that Damon Knight has. He's written quality short stories and

00:50.160 --> 00:57.940
novels, of course, since his first published work over 40 years ago in 1941. But
he's done so much else for the field. He's recognized as the first, and perhaps

00:57.940 --> 01:04.560
still the best, critic of science fiction. He founded the Science Fiction
Writers of America, and he initiated the Milford Science Fiction Writers

01:04.560 --> 01:12.160
Conference for authors of science fiction. He's also one of the premier editors
in science fiction, having constructed enough anthologies to fill a library. We

01:12.160 --> 01:18.120
spoke with Knight recently and asked him how he got his start in science
fiction. I thought that might come up, and I was rooting about it a little

01:18.120 --> 01:18.520
yesterday.

01:21.520 --> 01:31.440
Actually, I was thinking, what if you asked me to what do I attribute my
gigantic success? I would have to say mostly luck. I can trace my career back

01:31.440 --> 01:41.800
through a series of just astounding coincidences, really unlikely things, all
the way back to Hugo Gernsback. And I can demonstrate that at each of these

01:41.800 --> 01:49.840
points, if something rather unlikely had not happened, I wouldn't be doing what
I'm doing. For instance, if Hugo Gernsback had not come to this country from

01:49.840 --> 01:55.680
Luxembourg when he was 14 and started a magazine called Amazing Stories in 1926,

01:58.040 --> 02:05.280
you'll see as I go on that none of the other things could have happened. So here
I am, a 13-year-old kid in Hood River, Oregon, reading science fiction

02:05.280 --> 02:17.160
magazines, really turned on by them. And through the back pages of one of these
magazines, Super Science Stories, then edited by Frederick Bull, I found out

02:17.160 --> 02:26.660
about fanzines and wrote away for a few. And this boy got into correspondence
with the Futurians. The Futurians were a group of young science fiction fans who

02:26.660 --> 02:34.340
later became some of the major writers and editors in the field. At the time,
they included Frederick Pohl, Donald A. Walheim, Cyril Kornbluth, and Robert W.

02:34.520 --> 02:45.120
Lowndes. I was trying to write some stories, and I sent a couple to Lowndes, who
was then acting as a sort of half-assed literary agent. And all these things

02:45.120 --> 02:56.400
added up together until Donald A. Walheim got an offer from a publisher to edit
a new science fiction magazine. He had no budget whatever for stories. And he

02:56.400 --> 03:05.140
knew about me from Lowndes. Lowndes wrote to me saying, Will you donate this
story to the first issue of Super, a stirring science story? And of course I

03:05.140 --> 03:15.260
said yes. I would have paid for the privilege. And as a consequence of that, the
Futurians invited me to come and be a Futurian, and live in one of their

03:15.260 --> 03:25.720
communal dwellings in New York when I was 18. Terribly unlikely thing. Just a
series of them, even as far as it's gone. And I lived there a couple of years

03:25.720 --> 03:40.140
doing a little illustration for magazines and trying to write, not repeating
very much. And then in 1943, again, it was Fred Pohl, got me a job at Popular

03:40.140 --> 03:49.760
Publications where he was working. I needed an assistant editor. And he knew I
would work cheap. So he got me an interviewer. I got the job. Spent about a year

03:49.760 --> 03:58.940
there. And I'm perfectly convinced now, looking back, that it was that training
at Popular Publications that enabled me to write fiction professionally. It was

03:58.940 --> 04:06.800
a training that you couldn't get in any school then. I doubt if you could get it
now. But it just kind of soaked in because I was reading The Slush Pile, the

04:06.800 --> 04:14.080
unsolicited manuscripts, and it became perfectly obvious after a while what the
difference was between the stuff we were rejecting and the stuff we were

04:14.080 --> 04:17.560
printing. So when I quit that job, I started writing.

04:26.760 --> 04:34.140
Knight began publishing science fiction stories, many of which have become
classics today. But he also continued his editing and considers such work as the

04:34.140 --> 04:43.660
ideal training ground for young science fiction writers. If I could recommend a
writing course, a training course for young writers, I would certainly say it's

04:43.660 --> 04:52.500
too bad that those pulp magazines don't exist anymore. If you could possibly get
an editorial job or anything of that kind, even a terrible job in the Reading

04:52.500 --> 04:56.580
Sea Literary Agency to grab it. More with Damon Knight next time.

