06:31.140 --> 06:39.080
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Damon Knight's apprenticeship to science
fiction came as a member of the Futurians, a group of fans in the 1930s who

06:39.080 --> 06:47.000
later became some of the principal editors and writers in the field. Knight has
written a book about the Futurians, published in 1977. He reminisces about the

06:47.000 --> 06:59.760
group. Well, the Futurians were a very informal organization of science fiction
fans who were trying to become professionals. And in some cases had had little

06:59.760 --> 07:09.420
bits of success here and there in published stories. And I told you that Walheim
was editing a magazine. Before him, Pohl had become an editor. And after him,

07:09.580 --> 07:19.060
Lowndes also became an editor. And they were writing and publishing a little
bit, not much. And to save money, because they were all very poor, they lived in

07:19.060 --> 07:30.940
a communal apartment. At that time in New York, in the late 30s and early 40s,
there were lots of apartments that were very cheap. I forget now. I think the

07:30.940 --> 07:41.400
rental might have been about 30 bucks for a four-bedroom railroad flat. If you
had four people living there, it was quite cheap. And we divided up the

07:41.400 --> 07:52.280
household booties. Well, we did the cooking and I did the dish washing, which I
hated. We were dirt poor. We really didn't have any money at all. We rolled our

07:52.280 --> 07:59.160
own cigarettes and we bought the cheapest wine we could find, which was
something like 85 cents a gallon.

08:02.480 --> 08:12.100
Our major entertainment was walking down from 102nd Street or 103rd, if I was
down, to Times Square. And looking at the bright lights and having a cup of

08:12.100 --> 08:14.460
coffee in the cafeteria and walking home.

08:36.960 --> 08:44.780
Before Knight became recognized as an author of science fiction, he worked on
fanzines, as an editor, and as a book reviewer. Out of his experiences as a book

08:44.780 --> 08:51.280
reviewer, Knight developed some critical principles that he applied to science
fiction. And he actually became the first, and probably still the best, critic

08:51.280 --> 09:00.140
of the field. Knight talks about that period of his development in the 1940s
when he began writing criticism. I was trying to write fiction at that time and

09:00.140 --> 09:09.260
not succeeding. I couldn't finish stories. I didn't have any idea of how you got
to the end of the story. But I was extremely critical and starting, like any

09:09.260 --> 09:12.640
other bright 17 or 18-year-old fan.

09:15.580 --> 09:26.000
The first stuff I did for fanzines was not critical in the usual sense. I mean,
it wasn't book reviews or that kind of thing. But it was parody, mostly. The

09:26.000 --> 09:39.160
things that I thought were really outstandingly dumb in the magazine, funny
enough to parody. And I did a lot of that. But when I say a lot, I lie because I

09:39.160 --> 09:49.740
only published two issues of my fanzines and did very little for other
magazines. And it was much later, about 1945, I think, that I did a long

09:49.740 --> 10:01.040
critical essay about Van Gogh for one of Larry Shaw's amateur magazines. And
that was really the first critical work in the usual sense that I did. Knight's

10:01.040 --> 10:08.360
criticism and book reviews were published in 1967 as a book entitled In Search
of Wonder, a landmark since it was the first book of its kind. What Knight

10:08.360 --> 10:14.560
basically tried to do in his criticism was raise science fiction writing to a
higher level, to establish standards for it that would make it the equal of

10:14.560 --> 10:22.940
mainstream literature and quality. Well, that was my position then. I didn't see
any reason why science fiction shouldn't be as good as any other kind of fiction

10:22.940 --> 10:26.380
can be. I don't think now that it ever has been.

10:29.500 --> 10:41.020
And I still have a few doubts now about whether it can be. But at that time, as
you say, my effort was to try to raise the standards, improve the breed, mainly

10:41.020 --> 10:46.420
by shooting purples. On our next show, we'll continue our conversation with
Damon Knight.

