18:14.180 --> 18:23.300
This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. Damon Knight's best science fiction has a
real cutting edge to it, some sort of satire, irony, or social criticism. A good

18:23.300 --> 18:31.020
example is a second novel published in 1959 as The People Maker, but reissued
under Knight's preferred title, A for Anything. The story focuses on the

18:31.020 --> 18:38.740
question of how society would change if a matter duplicator were suddenly given
to mankind. The duplicator, called the gizmo, can copy anything, a tool, a

18:38.740 --> 18:46.480
building, a weapon, a vehicle, even a human being. Optimists may think society
would be enormously benefited from such a device, but that's not the way it

18:46.480 --> 18:53.780
turns out in Knight's novel. Quite the reverse. The social structure becomes
futile, with a few rich and powerful families controlling everything through the

18:53.780 --> 19:01.460
power of the gizmo. And slavery is a fact of life, too. The majority of the
people are poor and exploited by the powerful. For most of the novel, it seems

19:01.460 --> 19:09.000
the protagonist, the son of a rich and powerful gizmo owner, will aid in a slave
revolt which will overthrow the oppressive society. But on the final page of the

19:09.000 --> 19:16.180
novel, he shoots the wise old slave who has been leading the revolt, and chooses
to remain a rich tyrant. It's got to be one of the most depressing endings a

19:16.180 --> 19:24.940
science fiction novel ever had. We asked Knight why he produced it. Well, what
you're talking about, the ending that you expected, is the cliché ending.

19:26.080 --> 19:35.740
Romantic and sentimental. So I wanted to do a realistic ending. I thought that
the happy ending to that, you know, a conventional, quote, happy ending to that

19:35.740 --> 19:43.700
novel would have been false. And this was one of the things that interested me
in writing the novel in the first place. You know, anything I've done, in fact,

19:43.700 --> 19:55.160
except for the lapsing. I was trying to do science fiction realistically. I
thought that was part of the new wave. It wasn't called that then, but the wave

19:55.160 --> 20:05.420
of realism that came in the 50s. And I was awfully excited, still am, of the
romantic clichés of science fiction. We asked Knight why such a marvelous device

20:05.420 --> 20:17.160
as the gizmo would result in a tyrannical, slave-oriented society. Well, I
thought it was logical. I was counterpunching in that novel against some other

20:17.160 --> 20:29.080
treatments of the same device, the same gadgets that had been published before,
which I thought were cop-outs. For instance, George Oaks Smith wrote one in

20:29.080 --> 20:37.600
which the matter-type duplicator was invented. And, of course, chaos ensued, and
he rescued the world by inventing a kind of currency that couldn't be

20:37.600 --> 20:48.740
duplicated. And that was one too many rabbits out of the hat, I thought. So,
again, I just wanted to do it realistically. It seemed to me that if I had made

20:48.740 --> 21:04.800
a good case, that, in fact, slavery would be the result, I admit that it was an
imaginative projection. I don't necessarily defend the idea that that's what

21:04.800 --> 21:15.080
would happen in practice. And another writer, several years later, wrote a story
in response to that one, which really delighted me. I liked its dialogue aspect

21:15.080 --> 21:27.400
of science fiction, in which he showed that a good marketer, a good businessman,
could get along perfectly well and make money, even if there was a matter

21:27.400 --> 21:36.560
-duplicated. Marvelous story. We compared Knight's novel with Pole and
Kornblues' The Space Merchants, also published in the 1950s, and also a sharp

21:36.560 --> 21:47.060
criticism of society. We asked him if criticism of that sort was normal in
science fiction of the 50s. No, I think Fred Bowles and Kornblues' The Space

21:47.060 --> 22:01.560
Merchants, a gravy planet that was published in the magazine, was a stunning
rejection of the kind of thematic cliché that had been dominant in science

22:01.560 --> 22:12.160
fiction up until that time. And there had been social satire in science fiction
for a long time before during science fiction. And the magazine published some

22:12.160 --> 22:21.300
of it, but it was pretty remote. It didn't have the cutting edge that the gravy
planet had. More with Damon Knight next time.

