23:54.400 --> 24:02.800
This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. A clever, sharp wit characterizes the
science fiction of Damon Knight. His work is for the thinking reader, the type

24:02.800 --> 24:10.740
who appreciates irony, satire, unexpected twist and plot and ending. Much of his
fiction is characterized by a critical or negative tone. His stories, for

24:10.740 --> 24:18.260
example, seldom have happy endings. We asked him if he was a pessimistic person.
I'm not a pessimistic person in my daily life.

24:21.540 --> 24:32.160
I hate the word optimistic, but I'm cheerful most of the time. And I have a lot
of fun. I don't worry too much about disasters in the future. I certainly don't

24:32.160 --> 24:48.500
enjoy seeing people flip on banana peels. But I like irony and surprising people
in his stories. I dislike very much the story that says everything is going to

24:48.500 --> 24:56.740
be rosy and says it in a very implausible way and everybody laughs it up. I
don't know why. One of the stories in which Knight surprises his readers is

24:56.740 --> 25:05.100
entitled To Serve Man. It concerns a race of aliens who arrive on the Earth and
immediately put their superior technology to work to benefit the human race. One

25:05.100 --> 25:12.880
of the humans' chances on a book of the aliens. He works hard to translate it
and renders the title as To Serve Man. Everyone is pleased at the aliens' great

25:12.880 --> 25:20.240
generosity and kindness until they find out on the last page of the story that
the volume is a cookbook. Another witty effort is a story called The Country of

25:20.240 --> 25:29.020
the Kind. It takes place in a future world in which the entire human race is
kind, humane, and benevolent. Except for one single individual, a throwback, who

25:29.020 --> 25:36.000
is miserable because his violence and cruelty are tolerated by the general
society around him. The story almost makes you feel sorry for the cruel and

25:36.000 --> 25:43.660
destructive man, since his insane actions have absolutely no effect on the
blandness he's surrounded by. Knight's latest work, a novel entitled The World

25:43.660 --> 25:51.880
and Thorin, is one that he spent some 15 years on. It seems a departure from his
previous writing, and in fact the Berkeley paperback edition is labeled fantasy.

25:52.180 --> 26:03.900
But Knight disagrees with that designation. In the little introductory section
of the chapter, I thought I had laid out more or less what happened. But someone

26:03.900 --> 26:04.780
was about to go nova.

26:09.420 --> 26:23.880
People made a spaceship out of the Earth and propelled it out of the solar
system. And also went underground to accommodate the increasing population. Put

26:23.880 --> 26:35.160
the planet under the control of a central computer. And when there was a war
which destroyed civilization, the complete control was turned over to the

26:35.160 --> 26:51.880
computer, was directed to do whatever was necessary for the welfare of human
beings. And since the computer had not been told what welfare meant to human

26:51.880 --> 27:04.100
beings, it had to try to figure out what was the best society. And therefore,
having sealed up these caverns in order to prevent another war, it promoted the

27:04.100 --> 27:15.540
growth of different kinds of cultures, each one in each full cavern, hoping to
find out eventually what the best one was. Hope was passed. But that was the

27:15.540 --> 27:24.600
world in which the novel takes place. I really thought I had indicated that
sufficiently, but perhaps not. The world in Thorin is an episodic narrative. The

27:24.600 --> 27:32.200
protagonist, a lame young man named Thorin, journeys through caverns under the
Earth. And each cavern contains a separate race and a separate culture. And

27:32.200 --> 27:38.400
Thorin has an adventure of sorts with each one of them. Some of the episodes
seem like complete short stories, and we asked Knight if they were published

27:38.400 --> 27:48.060
separately. That's right. Fred Thorin ran, I think, three of them in Galaxy. And
you have to go pretty far back in the files to find them, because it did take me

27:48.060 --> 27:55.620
15 years to finish it. The world in Thorin doesn't have the bite or the satire
that characterizes much of Knight's work, but it's an enjoyable and exciting

27:55.620 --> 28:00.980
novel. And this is what readers have come to expect of Damon Knight, one of the
all-time masters of science fiction.

